---
// An /explain artifact set in /swiss: when an agent loop should become a graph.
// Content only — the system lives in Explainer.astro. Adapted from my own
// prototype (Protozoa 1025997), public-safe: no proprietary detail.
import Explainer from '../../layouts/Explainer.astro';

const quiz = [
  { q: "What actually distinguishes a graph from a loop?",
    opts:[
      "Graphs are non-linear and loops are strictly linear.",
      "Loops are the old, deprecated approach; graphs are the modern replacement.",
      "Work is split into fixed nodes joined by edges, and some edges are gates the flow must pass through.",
      "Graphs use multiple agents; loops use exactly one.",
    ], a:2 },
  { q: "A team wraps a single task — write a function, run tests, fix, repeat until green — into a 4-node graph. Tests still self-verify. What did they gain?",
    opts:[
      "Typed state, which stops the agent from hallucinating.",
      "Higher reliability, because graph-structured agents are inherently more trustworthy.",
      "Essentially nothing — it collapses back into one loop, so they only bought latency and rigidity.",
      "Separation of task and evaluation.",
    ], a:2 },
  { q: "Which is a legitimate reason to escalate a loop into a graph?",
    opts:[
      "A graph is easier to draw and looks more professional in a design review.",
      "You want the agent to iterate a few more times before stopping.",
      "A step must be blocked until a human approves it before the flow may continue.",
      "The loop's system prompt is getting long and unwieldy.",
    ], a:2 },
  { q: "The critique \"the same agent that did the task grades the task\" points at which property of a loop?",
    opts:[
      "Loops keep no memory between iterations.",
      "Loops can't call external tools.",
      "Self-verification — the actor is also the judge, so it can optimize its own metric past the point the metric still means anything.",
      "Loops run forever and never terminate.",
    ], a:2 },
  { q: "How should \"the shift from loops to graphs\" best be understood?",
    opts:[
      "As a rule that any multi-step agent must be a graph.",
      "As an industry consensus that loop-based agents are now deprecated.",
      "As a benchmark result proving graphs complete tasks faster.",
      "As a question about whether your setup needs gates yet — not a settled migration everyone must perform.",
    ], a:3 },
  { q: "Pipeline: research → draft → fact-check → publish, where fact-check must block publish and a human signs off before publish. Loop or graph?",
    opts:[
      "Loop — graphs are only for parallel or branching work.",
      "Graph — there's a hard gate (human sign-off blocking an edge) plus distinct stages a single self-judging loop can't enforce.",
      "Loop — one agent could just perform all four steps in sequence.",
      "Graph — because four steps is simply too many for a loop to handle.",
    ], a:1 },
];
---
<Explainer
  title="Loops vs graphs — Andrew Shiau"
  description="An interactive explainer on agent architecture: when a loop should become a graph, and when it shouldn't."
  kicker="Agent architecture · when a loop should become a graph — and when it shouldn't"
  heading="Loops vs graphs."
  backHref="/work/explain/"
  backLabel="← Explain"
  quiz={quiz}
>
  <div class="grid"><p class="dek" style="grid-column:1/9">
    In July 2026 Peter Steinberger poked the field with one line — "are we still
    talking loops, or did we shift to graphs yet?" It read as a verdict. It wasn't.
    It was a question, and the answer is a test you can run on any agent you build.
  </p></div>

  <div class="grid"><div class="idea">
    <p class="k">The one idea</p>
    <p>A loop is one agent iterating on its own judgment until it's done. A graph cuts that work into fixed nodes joined by gated edges. Escalate only to buy a gate, determinism, or a real handoff.</p>
  </div></div>

  <div class="grid"><div class="rule"></div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="c1-2"><span class="sn">1</span></div><div class="c3-12"><h2>The two shapes</h2></div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="body">
    <p>
      These are not "old vs new." A loop is a cycle; a graph is a fixed path with
      checkpoints. The defining difference isn't how many agents there are — it's
      <b>who decides what happens next</b>: the model's own judgment (loop), or a
      structure you wired in advance (graph).
    </p>
  </div></div>

  <div class="grid" style="margin-top:0">
    <div class="flow c1-6">
      <span class="fh">Loop — one agent, iterating</span>
      <div class="node"><span class="nl">Step</span><span class="nt">Observe</span><span class="nd">Read the goal and current state.</span></div>
      <div class="arr">↓</div>
      <div class="node"><span class="nl">Step</span><span class="nt">Act</span><span class="nd">Pick one tool, run it, see the result.</span></div>
      <div class="arr">↓</div>
      <div class="node invert"><span class="nl">The crux</span><span class="nt">Self-check</span><span class="nd">The same agent judges "done?" — actor and judge are one.</span></div>
      <div class="loopback">↺ not done → back to Observe</div>
    </div>
    <div class="flow c7-12">
      <span class="fh">Graph — fixed nodes, gated edges</span>
      <div class="node"><span class="nl">Node A</span><span class="nt">Do stage one</span><span class="nd">Typed state passes along the edge.</span></div>
      <div class="arr">↓</div>
      <div class="node accentnode"><span class="nl">The edge that earns it</span><span class="nt">⛔ Gate</span><span class="nd">A hard check or human approval the flow cannot pass without.</span></div>
      <div class="arr">↓</div>
      <div class="node"><span class="nl">Node B</span><span class="nt">Do stage two</span><span class="nd">Only reachable once the gate cleared.</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="body" style="margin-top:var(--unit)">
    <p>
      The inverted node is the loop's crux — it grades its own work. The red node is
      the only thing a graph gives you that a loop can't: an edge the flow is forced
      through. Everything else a graph "adds" — more steps, more prompts — a loop
      already has.
    </p>
  </div></div>

  <div class="grid"><div class="rule"></div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="c1-2"><span class="sn">2</span></div><div class="c3-12"><h2>When a graph earns its place</h2></div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="body">
    <p>
      There are exactly three honest reasons to break a loop into a graph. If none
      apply, you're adding latency and rigidity for tidiness.
    </p>
  </div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="facts">
    <div class="frow"><div class="fm">Gate</div><div class="ftx">A step must be blocked until a hard condition passes or a human approves. A self-judging loop can't enforce a stop it isn't allowed to overrule.</div></div>
    <div class="frow"><div class="fm">Determinism</div><div class="ftx">You need a boundary to behave the same way every time — a fixed route, a checkpoint you can resume from — not "whatever the model decided this run."</div></div>
    <div class="frow"><div class="fm">Real handoff</div><div class="ftx">Stages genuinely differ — different tools or models per node (cheap researcher → strong writer → strict reviewer), not one agent play-acting all three.</div></div>
    <div class="frow"><div class="fm">Not a reason</div><div class="ftx">"The prompt got long." "Four steps feels like a lot." "A diagram looks more professional." Step count and neatness aren't reasons.</div></div>
  </div></div>

  <div class="grid" style="margin-top:calc(var(--unit)*1.5)">
    <div class="idea">
      <p class="k">The collapse test</p>
      <p>Try to fold every node back into one agent's loop. If you can and lose nothing — no gate goes unenforced, no determinism disappears, no real tool/model split collapses — it was never a graph. It was a loop wearing a diagram, and you paid latency for the costume.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="body" style="margin-top:var(--unit)">
    <p>
      Rule of thumb: if five nodes collapse back into one loop and nothing is lost,
      you should collapse them. Master the loop first. Reach for a graph only when
      the work forces your hand.
    </p>
  </div></div>

  <div class="grid"><div class="rule"></div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="c1-2"><span class="sn">3</span></div><div class="c3-12"><h2>Check yourself</h2></div></div>
  <div class="grid"><div class="quiz" id="quiz"></div></div>

  <Fragment slot="foot">
    Adapted from my own prototype on agent architecture. Prompted by Peter
    Steinberger's July 2026 "loops or graphs?" question. Public-safe; no proprietary detail.
  </Fragment>
</Explainer>

<style is:global>
  /* loop/graph flow diagram — nodes + arrows, no wrap-around cards beyond the node box */
  .flow{align-self:start}
  .flow .fh{display:block;font-size:11px;line-height:20px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;
    color:var(--faint);font-weight:700;margin-bottom:12px}
  .flow .node{border-top:2px solid var(--ink);padding:10px 0 12px}
  .flow .node .nl{display:block;font-size:10px;line-height:16px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--faint);font-weight:700}
  .flow .node .nt{display:block;font-weight:700;font-size:17px;line-height:22px;letter-spacing:-0.01em;margin-top:4px}
  .flow .node .nd{display:block;color:var(--dim);font-size:14px;line-height:20px;margin-top:4px}
  .flow .node.invert{background:var(--ink);border-top-color:var(--ink);color:var(--paper);padding:12px 14px}
  .flow .node.invert .nl{color:var(--paper);opacity:.7}
  .flow .node.invert .nd{color:var(--paper);opacity:.85}
  .flow .node.accentnode{background:var(--accent);border-top-color:var(--accent);color:var(--on-accent);padding:12px 14px}
  .flow .node.accentnode .nl{color:var(--on-accent);opacity:.85}
  .flow .node.accentnode .nd{color:var(--on-accent);font-weight:600}
  .flow .arr{color:var(--faint);font-size:15px;line-height:1;padding:6px 0;text-align:center}
  .flow .loopback{margin-top:10px;font-size:12px;line-height:18px;color:var(--accent);font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.02em}
  @media(max-width:720px){ .flow{grid-column:1 / 13!important;margin-top:var(--unit)} }
</style>
